g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Command pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by ...

g.text: The Command pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by enabling introduction of a new Command, referencing the same Receiver, without changing the Receiver. In contrast, if the Receiver inherits the Command interface (to gain Invoker reusability) then the Receiver can offer only one of its functionalities via this interface. Exposure of multiple functionalities would require a behavior switch of the Receiver and thus most likely change. Via the Command pattern we can introduce another Command and reference a different function of the same Receiver. The system can be extended without change ensuring stability in test and production code.

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: As expressed in point (1), the Command implementation is the ...

g.text: As expressed in point (1), the Command implementation is the connection between Invoker and Receiver. This connection enables more possibilities then ‘just’ parameterizing Invoker requests. Command objects can be queued and scheduled for execution at a later moment in time. E.g. a Thread Pool that needs to queue certain requests until a Thread becomes available to execute it.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Command Pattern entails both the negative and positive si...

g.text: The Command Pattern entails both the negative and positive side of the Open Closed Principle. The Command pattern introduces an additional form of indirection between Invoker and Receiver, namely the Command object. This indirection has negative impact on debuggability and navigability of the code.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Command pattern decouples Invoker from Receiver by introd...

g.text: The Command pattern decouples Invoker from Receiver by introducing a Command interface and a Command implementation. The Command interface is completely independent from the Receiver interface. This provides Invoker reusability. The same invoker can ‘act’ on series of different receivers. The Command interface is generic and might not ‘satisfy’ the Receiver. The Receiver requires certain information that is passed via arguments. This is where the Command implementation comes in. The Command implementation manages dependencies required to provide the necessary information to the Receiver. Alternatively, the Receiver can also implement this generic Command interface. This means the Command implementation is not required anymore. However, this brings implementation ‘difficulties’ in case we need to connect multiple functions of the same receiver to different Invokers.

g.title: Folded Corner.244

g.text: As expressed in point (2), the Command implementation can be applicable in multiple use-cases. One of them is to support ‘undoable’ operations. Command objects can be stored in a ‘history’ list. This list enables the possibility to traverse backwards and forwards to redo and undo a Command. (An example on how to implement undo/redo can be found on this website: https://matt.berther.io/2004/09/16/using-the-command-pattern-for-undo-functionality/)

g.title: Folded Corner.251
g.desc: The Command Pattern entails both the negative and positive si...

g.text: The Command Pattern entails both the negative and positive side of the Single Responsibility Principle. The Command pattern introduces an additional Command class instead of ‘binding’ the Invoker and the Receiver directly via an interface. This additional Command class makes logic more scattered, compared to an implementation where the Receiver directly fulfills this responsibility. As a result, the code becomes harder to comprehend.

g.title: Folded Corner.254
g.desc: The Command Pattern compliments the Single Responsibility pri...

g.text: The Command Pattern compliments the Single Responsibility principle by decoupling sender from receiver. This enhances testability and reusability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where Invoker and Receiver are decoupled by an interface only. Testability, because the dependency constraints (e.g. to resolve a request) that would normally reside inside the Receiver are now resolved by the Command object. The Command object uses the required dependencies to parametrize the Receiver. The Receiver will become easier to test, because of the smaller dependency model (less to mock) and a smaller problem window. Reusability, because Invoker is bounded to a generic Command interface and Receiver doesn’t have any familiarity of the request. This generic Command interface enables the Invoker to be reused across different Receivers of the system (e.g. a button class of a UI). The smaller dependency model of the Receiver, resolved by the Command object, contributes to Receiver reusability.

g.title: Folded Corner.263

g.text: The Command pattern can be used to log executed commands to disk. A log file is generated based on the Commands that are performed. Recovering from a crash involves reading the log file and re-executing the commands.

g.title: Folded Corner.269
g.desc: The Command Pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Pri...

g.text: The Command Pattern compliments the Interface Segregation Principle by making the Invoker dependent on a ‘focused’ Command interface. This overcomes the dependency on a possible ‘extensive’ interface of the Receiver. The dependency on a ‘focused’ Command interface enhances testability, reusability and maintainability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where Invoker and Receiver are decoupled by an interface only. Testability, because the mock effort will be lower and interface changes in unused functionality will not reflect on the Receiver mock used by the Invoker. Reusability, because Invoker doesn’t reference an ‘extensive’ Receiver interface directly, making the Invoker better reusable for other Receivers. Maintainability, because less re-compilation is required. A change in the Receiver interface will not reflect on the Invoker.
